Root Finding

ysaikai@unimelb.edu.au

These notes are based on Chapter 10 of Jones, O., Maillardet, R., & Robinson, A. (2009). Introduction to scientific programming and simulation using R. CRC Press.

Introduction

Let \(f\) be a continuous function. Then, a root is a solution of \(f(x)=0\).

Visually, a root is a point where the graph \(y=f(x)\) crosses the x-axis.

For example, in the interval \([0,10]\), there are two roots of \(f\) defined below:

plot(c(1,7), c(0,0), pch = 19,
     xlim=c(0,10), ylim=c(-1050,1050),
     xlab="x", ylab="y",
     main=expression(y==x^4-37*x^3+447*x^2-1867*x+1456))
curve((x-1)*(x-7)*(x-13)*(x-16), from=0, to=10, add=TRUE)
abline(h=0)
text(1, 100, "root at x = 1", pos=4)
text(7, -100, "root at x = 7", pos=4)

Root finding is important because:

  • Factorisation of a polynomial, one of the most popular classes of functions (e.g., Taylor series approximation). For example, \[\begin{align} f(x) &= x^4-37x^3+447x^2-1867x+1456\\ &= (x-1)(x-7)(x-13)(x-16) \end{align}\]
  • Many problems can be modelled as root finding of suitable functions. Remember that finding a root of \(f(x)\) is equivalent to solving an equation \(g(x)=h(x)\) where \(f(x) = g(x)-h(x)\).

Loan repayments

Lets suppose:

  • \(P_n\) : Remaining amount of loan after \(n\) months
  • \(P\) : Initial amount of loan (i.e., \(P_0 = P\))
  • \(N\) : Duration of repayments
  • \(A\) : Monthly repayment amount
  • \(r\) : Monthly interest rate

Given \(P_{n-1}\), we know: \[P_n = (1+r)P_{n-1} - A\] That is, each month, interest based on \(P_{n-1}\) is added and then you repay \(A\).

The solution of the difference equation (i.e., the expression of \(P_n\) as a function of \(n\)) is:

\[ P_n = (1+r)^nP - \frac{A}{r}\left((1+r)^n-1\right) \]

To see this, for each \(k\in\{1,\dots,n\}\), multiply both sides of \(P_k = (1+r)P_{k-1} - A\) by \((1+r)^{n-k}\) and get a telescoping sum.

We negotiate with a bank on the interest rate. A question is under what \(r\), can we repay the loan after \(N\) months?

We could get the answer by solving \(P_N=0\) for \(r\): \[\begin{align} P_N &= 0\\ \Leftrightarrow (1+r)^NP &= \frac{A}{r}\left((1+r)^N-1\right)\\ \Leftrightarrow (1+r)^N &= \frac{A}{A-rP}\\ &\vdots \end{align}\] Well, this is hard (at least for me). Instead, we may use numerical root-finding methods for \(f(r) = P_N\).

Fixed-point iteration

Fixed point

Let \(g: \mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}\) be a continuous function. Then, a fixed point of \(g\) is a solution of \(g(x)=x\).

Visually, a fixed point is a point where the graph \(y=g(x)\) crosses the 45-degree line.

For example, a hyperbolic tangent \[g(x) = 2\tanh(x) = 2\frac{e^{x}-e^{-x}}{e^{x}+e^{-x}}\] has three fixed points: \(x = -1.915, 0, 1.915\).

x <- c(-1.915,0,1.915)
y <- c(-1.915,0,1.915)
plot(x, y, pch = 19, xlim=c(-2,2), ylim=c(-2,2))
title(expression(y==2*tanh(x)))
curve(2*tanh(x), from=-3, to=3, add=TRUE)
curve(x*1, from=-3, to=3, add=TRUE)
text(-1.55, -.8, "fixed point at -1.915")
text(0, -.2, "fixed point at 0", pos=4)
text(1.55, .8, "fixed point at 1.915")
arrows(-1.8, -1, -1.9, -1.8, length=0.1)
arrows(1.8, 1, 1.9, 1.8, length=0.1)

Given \(f\), root finding is to compute a value \(a\) such that \(f(a)=0\). But, as long as we legally manipulate the equation \(f(a)=0\), the same \(a\) satisfies both the original \(f(a)=0\) and transformed equations. This is why we may turn root finding into fixed-point problems. Among many possible ways to manipulate \(f(a)=0\), the following is perhaps the simplest. \[f(a)=0 \Leftrightarrow f(a)+a=a\] Then, we define a new function \(g\) such that \(g(x)=f(x)+x\) and try to find a fixed point of \(g\) to find a root of \(f\).

Clearly, this is not the only way of transformation and, as seen below, the performance of fixed-point iteration depends on how we transform \(f(a)=0\) and define \(g\).

Method

The fixed-point iteration is a method for solving \(g(x)=x\) by iteratively generating points \(x_0,x_1,\dots\) that, we hope, converge to \(a\) such that \(g(a)=a\).

Given \(x_n\), the generation of points follows a simple difference equation \(x_{n+1}=g(x_n)\). Clearly, to start somewhere at \(n=0\), we need an initial guess (\(x_0\)).

If a sequence \(\{x_n\}\) converges to some point \(a\), then the continuity of \(g\) implies that \(a\) is indeed a fixed point of \(g\).

\[a = \lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n+1} = \lim_{n\to\infty}g(x_n) = g\left(\lim_{n\to\infty}x_n\right) = g(a)\]

An issue of fixed-point iteration is that convergence of \(\{x_n\}\) is not guaranteed but depends on \(g\) and \(x_0\).

For example, in the case of \(g(x)=2\tanh(x)\), \(\{x_n\}\) converges no matter what \(x_0\) is.

x <- c(.2,0.395,0.4,0.751,0.751,1.271,1.271,1.708,1.708,
       -.2,-0.395,-0.4,-0.751,-0.751,-1.271,-1.271,-1.708,-1.708)

Can you follow how arrows move? Basically, a point on the graph \(y=g(x)\) moves horizontally to the 45-degree line because the current \(y\) value, say \(y=g(x_n)\), becomes a new \(x=x_{n+1}\) value. Then, it moves vertically to the graph and gets a new \(y=g(x_{n+1})\) value.

In contrast, in the case of \(g(x)=e^x-1\), \(\{x_n\}\) converges if \(x_0\leq0\) and diverges if \(x_0>0\).

x <- c(.5,0.65,0.65,0.916,0.916,1.5,

In general, a fixed point \(a\) is stable if \(|g'(a)|<1\) and unstable if \(|g'(a)|>1\).

Visually, assuming \(g'(a)>0\), \(a\) is stable if the graph of \(g\) crosses the 45-degree line from above and unstable if crossing from below.

Now suppose \(\{x_n\}\) converges to \(a\), which is usually reached only in the limit (\(n\to\infty\)). In practice, we cannot iterate forever and must stop at some point. So, we commonly use the following stopping criteria:

  • \(|x_n-x_{n-1}|\leq\epsilon\), where \(\epsilon\) is a small positive number
  • \(n=max.iter\), where \(max.iter\) is the maximum number of iterations allowed

Root of \(\log(x)-\exp(-x)\)

First, lets draw \(y=\log(x)-\exp(-x)\). It seems the root sits between 1.0 and 1.5.

x <- c(1.31)
y <- c(0)
plot(x, y, pch = 19, xlim=c(0,2), ylim=c(-3,1))
text(x, -.2, "unique fixed point", pos=4)
title(expression(y==log(x)-exp(-x)))
curve(log(x)-exp(-x), xlab="x", ylab="y", from=0, to=4, add=TRUE)
abline(h=0)

As mentioned above, there are many ways to manipulate \(f(x)=0\) and define the corresponding \(g\). In this example, we examine three different transformations:

\[\begin{align} g_1(x) &= \exp(\exp(-x))\\ g_2(x) &= x-\log{x}+\exp(-x)\\ g_3(x) &= x+\log{x}-\exp(-x) \end{align}\]

Using the package spuRs, it is quite easy to run the fixed-point iteration. After loading the package with library(spuRs), we may simply define \(g\) and pass it to fixedpoint function with an initial guess (e.g., \(x_0=1.5\)).

fixedpoint has default values for the stopping criteria, tol = 1e-09 and max.iter = 100 (tol for our \(\epsilon\)). Check its document by typing help("fixedpoint"). Also, try different values and see how the result changes.

The code may look like this.

g2 <- function(x){
  return(x - log(x) + exp(-x))
}
a2 <- fixedpoint(g2, 1.5)
## At iteration 1 value of x is: 1.317665 
## At iteration 2 value of x is: 1.309564 
## At iteration 3 value of x is: 1.309807 
## At iteration 4 value of x is: 1.309799 
## At iteration 5 value of x is: 1.3098 
## At iteration 6 value of x is: 1.3098 
## At iteration 7 value of x is: 1.3098 
## Algorithm converged

As you will see after running the code for all of three \(g\), for both \(g_1\) and \(g_2\), we find the fixed point of 1.31, but fail for \(g_3\). Also, note that the search is faster for \(g_2\) than for \(g_1\).

The results illustrate that the fixed-point iteration has some disadvantage. We need to transform \(f(x)=0\) into suitable \(g(x)=x\), and some forms of \(g\) perform much better than others. This is inconvenient. In our example, while \(g_3\) is in a sense the most natural form satisfying \(f(x)=g(x)-x\), it has the worst performance. In stark contrast, \(g_2\) obtained simply from \(-f(x)=0\) has the best performance.

Newton-Raphson method

The Newton-Raphson method uses linear approximation of \(f(x)\) to generate a sequence of guesses at a root (\(a\)).

Remember that linear approximation (i.e., the 1st-degree Taylor approximation) of \(f(x)\) at \(x_n\) is \[f(x) \approx f(x_n)+f'(x_n)(x-x_n) .\] Thanks to the linearity, it is easy to find a root (\(\hat{a}\)) of the approximated function: \[\begin{align} & f(x_n)+f'(x_n)(\hat{a}-x_n) = 0\\ \Leftrightarrow\quad & \hat{a} = x_n - \frac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)} \end{align}\]

Now, suppose that \(x_n\) is the current guess at \(a\). Then, given the approximated function, it is natural to see the estimated root (\(\hat{a}\)) as an improved guess. This is the idea behind the Newton-Raphson method: \[ x_{n+1} = x_n - \frac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)} .\]

Similar to the fixed-point iteration, we cannot guarantee convergence of the Newton-Raphson method. But, If a sequence \(\{x_n\}\) converges to some point \(a\), then \(a\) is indeed a fixed point of \(f\) under some conditions. Specifically, suppose that \(f\) is continuously differentiable, and that \(f'\) is bounded. Then, \[\begin{align} a &= \lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n+1}\\ &= \lim_{n\to\infty} \left( x_n - \frac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)} \right)\\ &= \lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n} - \frac{f(\lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n})}{f'(\lim_{n\to\infty}x_{n})}\\ &= a - \frac{f(a)}{f'(a)} , \end{align}\] which implies \(f(a)=0\) because \(|f'(a)|\) is finite.

There are also similar stopping criteria:

  • \(|f(x_n)|\leq\epsilon\), where \(\epsilon\) is a small positive number
  • \(n=max.iter\), where \(max.iter\) is the maximum number of iterations allowed

Can you see why the first criterion makes sense?

Root of \(\log(x)-\exp(-x)\)

Lets apply the Newton-Raphson method to the same \(f(x)=\log(x)-\exp(-x)\).

With spuRs, it is quite easy to run the Newton-Raphson method. Define both \(f\) and \(f'\), and pass them to newtonraphson function with an initial guess (e.g., \(x_0=1.5\)).

Results look like this.

fd <- function(x){
  f <- log(x) - exp(-x)
  df <- 1/x + exp(-x)
  return(c(f,df))
}
a <- newtonraphson(fd, 1.5)
## At iteration 1 value of x is: 1.295082 
## At iteration 2 value of x is: 1.30971 
## At iteration 3 value of x is: 1.3098 
## At iteration 4 value of x is: 1.3098 
## Algorithm converged

As you can see, it finds the same root \((= 1.31)\) with fewer iterations than the fixed-point iteration. The better performance is mainly because the Newton-Raphson method makes use of the extra information, namely the derivative.

Considering the task of root findingsearch for a point where \(f(x)\) crosses the x-axisknowing \(f'(x)\) is quite useful because it tells the direction in which \(f(x)\) increases. Intuitively, if we currently have \(f(x_n)>0\), we want to follow the opposite direction of \(f'(x)\) to get closer to a root.

Secant method

A motivation for the secant method is What if we do not have access to the derivative? It happens because the derivative can be very expensive to compute or even does not exist at all. Using the secant method, we can use the same idea of linear approximation of \(f(x)\) without the derivative.

As the name suggests, the method substitutes the slope of secant line for the derivative.

Suppose that \(x_{n-1}\) and \(x_n\) are the current guesses at a root. Then, an estimate of \(f'(x_n)\) is \(\frac{f(x_n)-f(x_{n-1})}{x_n-x_{n-1}}\). Now, we can simply substitute this for the derivative used in the Newton-Raphson method to get the secant method. \[\begin{align} x_{n+1} &= x_n - \frac{f(x_n)}{\frac{f(x_n)-f(x_{n-1})}{x_n-x_{n-1}}}\\ &= x_n - f(x_n)\frac{x_n-x_{n-1}}{f(x_n)-f(x_{n-1})} \end{align}\]

x <- c(1.31)
y <- c(0)
plot(x, y, pch = 19, xlim=c(0,2), ylim=c(-3,1))
text(x, -.2, "unique fixed point", pos=4)
title(expression(y==log(x)-exp(-x)))
curve(log(x)-exp(-x), xlab="x", ylab="y", from=0, to=4, add=TRUE)
abline(h=0)
points(c(.5,.2,0.998,0.844), c(-1.3,-2.43,0,0), cex=.7)
curve(2.61*x-2.605, from=.05, to=1.15, add=TRUE)
curve(3.77*x-3.18, from=.05, to=.95, add=TRUE)
text(.55, -1.5, expression(x[n]))
text(.27, -2.6, expression(x[n-1]))
arrows(.7, .6, 0.835, .05, length=0.1)
arrows(1.07, .67, 1.001, .06, length=0.1)
text(.6, .8, expression(paste(x[n+1]," by Secant")))
text(1.17, .9, expression(paste(x[n+1]," by NR")))

Due to the estimated derivative information, as expected, the secant method does not perform as well as the Newton-Raphson method. But, this is often a reasonable trade-off in practice.

Bisection method

While convergence is not guaranteed in none of the above methods, for the price of slowness, it is guaranteed in the bisection method.

The bisection method belongs to a class of root-finding algorithms called bracketing, which successively isolates smaller intervals (brackets) that contain a root. In the bisection method, a bracket is always halved at each iteration.

As always, we assume \(f\) to be a continuous function. Now, start with some interval \((x_l,x_r)\) such that \(f(x_l)f(x_r)<0\), i.e., the graph \(y=f(x)\) crosses the x-axis at least once. In other words, choose an interval in which a root exists. Next, evaluate \(f\) at the mid point \(x_m = (x_l+x_r)/2\) and see the sign of \(f(x_m)\). Update the interval with one of two halved intervals \((x_l,x_m)\) or \((x_m,x_r)\) that contains the root. Continue until the stopping criteria are met.

The following is a more precise algorithm that must start with \((x_l,x_r)\) such that \(f(x_l)f(x_r)<0\).

  1. Halt and return either \(x_l\) or \(x_r\) if \(x_l-x_r\leq\epsilon\).
  2. Set \(x_m = (x_l+x_r)/2\).
  3. Halt and return \(x_m\) if \(f(x_m)=0\).
  4. Set \(x_r=x_m\) if \(f(x_l)f(x_m)<0\). Otherwise, set \(x_l=x_m\).
  5. Go back to 1.

Lets apply the bisection method to the same function to the same \(f(x)=\log(x)-\exp(-x)\). In contrast to an initial point to fixedpoint and newtonraphson, in this case, we supply to bisection two boundary points of an initial interval (\(x_l\) and \(x_r\)).

f <- function(x){
  return(log(x) - exp(-x))
}
a <- bisection(f, 1, 2)

As you will see, it finds the same root \((= 1.31)\) after more iterations than the Newton-Raphson method needs.
